<subsection xml:id="subsec-volume-of-a-sphere">
    <title>Volume of a Sphere</title>
       <p>
        A sphere is a perfectly round object.
       </p>
       <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\textbf{Orange Peeling Experiment}</m>  
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Materials Needed:  
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ An orange (or any round fruit)
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ A knife
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ A flat surface
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <image>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define colors
                    \definecolor{orange}{rgb}{1,0.5,0}
                    \definecolor{green}{rgb}{0,0.6,0}

                    % Function to draw an orange with a single black dot near the leaf
                    \newcommand{\draworange}[2]{
                    % Draw the main orange
                    \filldraw[fill=orange,draw=black] (#1,#2) circle(1);
                    
                    % Add a black dot near the leaf
                    \fill[black] (#1+0.3,#2+0.8) circle(0.12);

                    % Add a green leaf
                    \filldraw[fill=green,draw=black,rotate around={30:(#1,#2+1)}] 
                    (#1,#2+1) ellipse (0.5 and 0.2);
                    }

                    % Bottom layer (4 oranges)
                    \foreach \x in {0,2,4,6} {
                        \draworange{\x}{0}
                    }

                    % Second layer (3 oranges)
                    \foreach \x in {1,3,5} {
                        \draworange{\x}{1.7}
                    }

                    % Third layer (2 oranges)
                    \foreach \x in {2,4} {
                        \draworange{\x}{3.4}
                    }

                    % Top layer (1 orange)
                    \draworange{3}{5.1}

                    % Ground surface
                    \draw[thick] (-1,-1) -- (7,-1);
                    
                    % Labels
                    \node at (3,-1.5) {Pyramidal Stack of Oranges};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
                
            </sidebyside>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Cut the orange in half and carefully peel the skin off in small sections.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Try flattening the peels and arrange them to see how they approximate a circleâ€™s area.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           ðŸ“Œ When you peel an orange and flatten the pieces, you can see that the peels cover a large area.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ This helps visualize why increasing the radius increases the overall amount of space the fruit takes up (its volume).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Cutting the Orange into Sections. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ If you cut an orange in half, you can see its cross-section.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           ðŸ“Œ  If you keep slicing it into smaller spheres, their individual radii determine their volumes.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Why do yopu think oranges or tomatoes or apples etc. are stacking in pyramidal stacks in the market?
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ Oranges in a fruit market are often packed in pyramidal stacks because spheres fit together efficiently.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ The larger the radius, the more space each orange occupies, which directly affects storage and packaging.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Key takeaways 
                        </p>

                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ The radius is the most important factor in determining the volume of a sphere.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ If the radius doubles, the volume increases by <m>2^3 = 8</m> times!
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            ðŸ“Œ This explains why a slightly bigger orange holds significantly more juice compared to a smaller one.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>    
        </statement>
       </activity>
       <example>
       <statement>
        <p>
             A sphere has a radius of 6 cm. Find its volume.
        </p>  
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> \text{V} =\amp \frac{4}{3} \times r^3</mrow>
            <mrow>  = \amp 3.142 \frac{4}{3} \times (6)^3</mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp \frac {864}{3} \times 3.142 </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp 904.32 \text{cm}^3</mrow>
          </md>  
        </p>
       </statement>
        
       </example>
       <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A football has a radius of 9 cm. What is the volume of the ball?
            </p>

        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{V} =\amp \frac{4}{3} \times r^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>  = \amp 3.142 \frac{4}{3} \times (9)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 3053.63 \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                </md>  
            </p>
        </solution>
       </example>
       <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A planet has a radius of 1000 km. What's it's volume?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{V} =\amp \frac{4}{3} \times r^3</mrow>
                    <mrow>  = \amp 3.142 \frac{4}{3} \times (1000)^3</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4.19 \times 10^9 \text{km}^3</mrow>
                </md>  
                
            </p>
        </solution>
       </example>
          
</subsection>